VALUES
(43, 20, 1, 41, 16, 9, 9, 'first day of the week', 'Mary Magdalene''s Encounter with Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Mary Magdalene''s role in discovering the resurrection of Jesus on the first day of the week. John 20:1 mentions her arriving at the sepulchre, while Mark 16:9 highlights her as the first to see the risen Jesus.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 1, 40, 27, 60, 60, 'stone taken away from the sepulchre', 'Connection of the Tomb and Stone', 'Both passages emphasize the stone related to the sepulchre. John 20:1 mentions the stone taken away, while Matthew 27:60 describes the stone rolled to the door of the sepulchre.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 1, 41, 15, 46, 46, 'sepulchre', 'Connection of the Sepulchre', 'Both passages emphasize the sepulchre where Jesus was laid. John mentions Mary Magdalene visiting the sepulchre, while Mark describes the sepulchre''s details and the stone at its entrance.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 1, 42, 24, 1, 10, 'the stone taken away from the sepulchre', 'Resurrection Announcement', 'Both passages emphasize the event of discovering the stone rolled away from the sepulchre. They highlight the significance of the first day of the week as the moment of Jesus'' resurrection, with Mary Magdalene being a key figure in both accounts.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 1, 43, 19, 25, 25, 'Mary Magdalene', 'Mary Magdalene''s Role', 'Both passages emphasize Mary Magdalene''s presence at significant events surrounding Jesus'' death and resurrection. Her mention at the cross in John 19:25 connects her to the discovery of the empty tomb in John 20:1.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 1, 43, 20, 18, 19, 'the first day of the week', 'Resurrection and Revelation', 'This connection highlights the significance of Mary Magdalene''s role in both passages. In John 20:1, she discovers the empty tomb, and in John 20:18-19, she shares her encounter with the risen Jesus, emphasizing her pivotal role in the resurrection narrative.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 1, 66, 1, 10, 10, 'the first day of the week', 'Connection of the Lord''s Day', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the first day of the week. John 20:1 mentions Mary Magdalene visiting the sepulchre early on this day, while Revelation 1:10 refers to being in the Spirit on the Lord''s day, indicating a special spiritual significance associated with this time.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 2, 43, 13, 23, 23, NULL, 'Connection of the Beloved Disciple', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of ''the disciple, whom Jesus loved.'' This connection highlights the special relationship between Jesus and this disciple, which is significant in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 2, 43, 20, 13, 13, NULL, 'Connection of Mourning and Loss', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of loss and mourning for Jesus. Mary expresses her sorrow in both instances, highlighting her distress over the missing body of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 2, 43, 19, 26, 26, NULL, 'Connection Between Beloved Disciple and Mary', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship of the beloved disciple to Jesus and his mother. The mention of ''the disciple whom Jesus loved'' in both verses highlights a significant bond that connects these moments in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 2, 43, 21, 24, 24, NULL, 'Testimony of the Beloved Disciple', 'This connection highlights the role of the disciple whom Jesus loved as a key witness. Both passages emphasize the importance of testimony regarding Jesus'' resurrection and the truth of the events surrounding it.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 2, 40, 27, 63, 64, 'They have taken away the Lord', 'Resurrection and Disciples'' Concern', 'This connection highlights the concern of the disciples regarding the body of Jesus. In John, Mary Magdalene reports the absence of Jesus, while in Matthew, the religious leaders express fear of the disciples stealing the body to claim resurrection.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 3, 42, 24, 12, 12, 'went forth, and that other disciple', 'Peter''s Visit to the Sepulchre', 'Both passages emphasize Peter''s action of going to the sepulchre. John 20:3 mentions Peter''s departure with another disciple, while Luke 24:12 describes Peter running to the sepulchre and observing the linen clothes.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 4, 10, 18, 23, 23, 'ran both together', 'Running to Deliver News', 'Both passages emphasize the act of running to deliver important news. In John 20:4, the disciples run to the sepulchre, while in 2 Samuel 18:23, Ahimaaz runs to deliver a message, highlighting the urgency and significance of their missions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 4, 46, 9, 24, 24, 'ran both together', 'Running and Competition Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the act of running as a metaphor for striving towards a goal. In John, the running signifies urgency and pursuit, while in Corinthians, it highlights the competitive nature of striving for a prize.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 4, 47, 8, 12, 12, 'first', 'Willingness and Effort in Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of effort and willingness in both passages. In John 20:4, the other disciple''s eagerness to reach the sepulchre first reflects a willing mind, which is echoed in 2 Corinthians 8:12 regarding acceptance based on one''s willingness.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 4, 3, 13, 30, 30, 'ran both together', 'Running and Examination Themes', 'This connection highlights the urgency in both passages. In John, the disciples run to the sepulchre, while in Leviticus, the priest must examine the plague closely. Both emphasize the importance of immediate action and careful observation.', 'theme', 0.286, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 5, 43, 19, 40, 40, 'linen clothes', 'Connection of Linen Clothes', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of linen clothes in the burial and resurrection of Jesus. The linen clothes mentioned in John 19:40 are directly referenced in John 20:5, highlighting their importance in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 5, 43, 11, 44, 44, 'linen clothes lying', 'Connection of Graveclothes and Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of graveclothes. In John 20:5, the linen clothes are noted as lying, while in John 11:44, the dead man is bound with graveclothes, highlighting the transition from death to life.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 5, 43, 20, 11, 11, 'stooping down, and looking in', 'Connection of Stooping and Looking', 'Both passages emphasize the act of stooping down and looking into the sepulchre. This connection highlights the shared physical action of the characters as they engage with the empty tomb.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 6, 40, 16, 15, 16, 'Simon Peter', 'Peter''s Recognition and Discovery', 'This connection highlights Peter''s role in both passages, where he acknowledges Jesus as the Christ and later discovers the empty tomb. Both moments signify pivotal revelations about Jesus'' identity and mission.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 6, 42, 22, 31, 32, 'Simon Peter', 'Peter''s Role in Faith', 'This connection highlights Peter''s journey from doubt to strength. In John, Peter witnesses the resurrection, while in Luke, Jesus emphasizes the importance of Peter''s faith and his future role in strengthening others.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 6, 43, 6, 67, 69, 'Simon Peter', 'Peter''s Recognition of Christ', 'This connection highlights Peter''s journey from witnessing the empty tomb to affirming Jesus as the Christ. Both passages emphasize Peter''s pivotal role in recognizing Jesus'' significance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 6, 43, 18, 17, 17, NULL, 'Peter''s Denial and Discovery', 'This connection highlights Peter''s journey from denial to discovery. In John 18:17, Peter denies being a disciple, while in John 20:6, he actively seeks the truth in the sepulchre.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 6, 43, 21, 7, 7, 'Simon Peter', 'Peter''s Recognition of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Simon Peter''s actions in response to the presence of Jesus. In the first, Peter enters the sepulchre, while in the second, he reacts to the news of Jesus'' appearance by jumping into the sea.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 7, 43, 11, 44, 44, 'napkin, that was about his head', 'Connection of Graveclothes and Napkin', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of a napkin associated with the dead. In John 11:44, the napkin is mentioned as part of the graveclothes, while in John 20:7, it is specifically noted as being separate and wrapped. This connection highlights the significance of the napkin in the context of resurrection.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 8, 43, 20, 25, 25, 'and he saw, and believed', 'Belief in the Resurrection', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief in the resurrection. In John 20:8, the disciple sees and believes, while in John 20:25, Thomas expresses doubt and requires physical proof to believe.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 8, 43, 20, 4, 4, 'came first to the sepulchre', 'Disciples'' Race to the Tomb', 'Both passages emphasize the other disciple''s speed and belief. The first mention of the disciple outrunning Peter sets the stage for the moment of belief when he sees the empty tomb.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 8, 43, 1, 50, 50, 'believed', 'Belief in Greater Things', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief in Jesus'' words and the promise of witnessing greater things. In both passages, belief is a central focus, with John 20:8 emphasizing belief upon seeing the empty tomb, and John 1:50 suggesting that belief leads to greater revelations.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 8, 43, 20, 29, 29, 'and believed', 'Belief in the Unseen', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief based on sight versus faith. In John 20:8, the disciple believes after seeing the empty tomb, while John 20:29 emphasizes the blessing of those who believe without seeing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 9, 19, 16, 10, 10, 'rise again from the dead', 'Resurrection and Corruption Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of resurrection, as John 20:9 indicates the necessity of Jesus rising from the dead, while Psalms 16:10 speaks to the Holy One not seeing corruption. Both passages emphasize the assurance of life after death.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 9, 23, 25, 8, 8, 'must rise again from the dead', 'Victory Over Death', 'This connection highlights the theme of resurrection and victory over death. John 20:9 indicates a lack of understanding regarding the necessity of resurrection, while Isaiah 25:8 proclaims God''s triumph over death.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 9, 23, 53, 10, 12, 'he must rise again from the dead', 'Resurrection and Suffering Servant', 'This connection highlights the theme of resurrection in John 20:9 and the suffering of the servant in Isaiah 53:10-12. Both passages emphasize the necessity of suffering leading to vindication and life, illustrating the fulfillment of prophecy regarding the Messiah''s role in bearing sin and rising again.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 9, 42, 24, 44, 46, 'they knew not the scripture', 'Resurrection Understanding Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of Christ''s resurrection. John highlights the disciples'' lack of understanding, while Luke shows Jesus explaining the fulfillment of scripture regarding his resurrection.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 9, 46, 15, 4, 4, 'that he must rise again from the dead', 'Resurrection and Scripture Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of resurrection as both passages address Jesus'' rising from the dead. John 20:9 notes the disciples'' lack of understanding of scripture regarding the resurrection, while 1 Corinthians 15:4 affirms that his resurrection occurred ''according to the scriptures.''', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 9, 42, 24, 26, 26, 'must rise again from the dead', 'Connection of Resurrection and Suffering', 'This connection highlights the necessity of Christ''s suffering before his resurrection. Both passages emphasize the idea that suffering precedes glory, as indicated by the phrases regarding rising from the dead and entering into glory.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 9, 28, 13, 14, 14, 'rise again from the dead', 'Resurrection and Redemption Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of resurrection and victory over death. John 20:9 speaks of Jesus'' resurrection, while Hosea 13:14 emphasizes God''s power to redeem from death and the grave.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 10, 43, 7, 53, 53, NULL, 'Disciples Returning Home', 'Both passages emphasize individuals going to their own homes, highlighting a common theme of personal retreat or return. This connection illustrates a moment of transition for the characters involved.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 10, 43, 16, 32, 32, NULL, 'Disciples'' Scattering and Isolation', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' separation from Jesus. In John 20:10, they return to their own homes, paralleling the scattering mentioned in John 16:32, where they leave Him alone.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 11, 43, 20, 5, 5, 'stooped down, and looked into', 'Connection of Stooping and Looking', 'Both passages emphasize the action of stooping down and looking into the sepulchre, highlighting a moment of inquiry and discovery. This connection illustrates a shared experience of observing the empty tomb.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 12, 42, 24, 3, 7, 'two angels in white sitting', 'Angels at the Tomb', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of two angels or men at the tomb of Jesus, providing reassurance about His resurrection. The angels in both accounts serve to clarify the significance of the empty tomb and the resurrection.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 12, 41, 16, 5, 6, 'angels in white', 'Angelic Presence at the Tomb', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of angels at Jesus'' tomb, signifying his resurrection. John mentions two angels, while Mark describes one, highlighting the divine confirmation of Jesus'' rising.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 12, 66, 3, 4, 4, 'in white', 'Angels and Garments in White', 'This connection highlights the theme of purity and divine presence. In John 20:12, the angels in white signify holiness, while in Revelation 3:4, those who walk in white represent worthiness and purity.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 12, 14, 5, 12, 12, 'in white', 'Angels and Priestly Garments', 'Both passages emphasize beings arrayed in white, suggesting a connection between divine presence and worship. The angels in John signify the resurrection, while the Levites in Chronicles represent sacred service.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 12, 27, 7, 9, 9, 'two angels in white', 'Angelic Presence and Divine Authority', 'This connection highlights the presence of angels in both passages, with John 20:12 describing two angels at the tomb of Jesus, while Daniel 7:9 presents the Ancient of Days in a majestic setting. Both emphasize the significance of divine beings in relation to God''s authority and the resurrection.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 12, 40, 17, 2, 2, 'in white', 'Angelic Presence and Divine Glory', 'This connection highlights the presence of angels and the theme of divine glory. In John 20:12, the angels are described as ''in white,'' paralleling the radiant appearance of Jesus in Matthew 17:2, where his raiment is ''white as the light.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 12, 40, 28, 2, 5, NULL, 'Angelic Presence at Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of angels at the resurrection of Jesus. In John, two angels are noted, while Matthew describes one angel who rolls back the stone, highlighting the divine involvement in the resurrection event.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 13, 43, 20, 15, 15, 'why weepest thou', 'Connection of Weeping and Seeking', 'Both passages emphasize the question, ''Why weepest thou?'' highlighting Mary''s emotional state. Additionally, both verses involve her seeking the whereabouts of Jesus, reinforcing her distress over his absence.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 13, 9, 1, 8, 8, 'why weepest thou?', 'Expressions of Grief', 'Both passages emphasize the question, ''why weepest thou?'' highlighting deep emotional distress. This connection illustrates a shared theme of sorrow and longing for what has been lost.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 13, 19, 43, 3, 5, 'why weepest thou?', 'Emotional Expressions of Grief', 'This connection highlights the theme of sorrow and longing for God. In John 20:13, the woman''s grief over the missing Lord parallels the psalmist''s inner turmoil and questioning in Psalms 43:5.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 13, 43, 2, 4, 4, 'Woman, why weepest thou?', 'Connection of Mourning and Timing', 'This connection highlights the emotional state of Mary in John 20:13, where she expresses sorrow over the absence of Jesus. Similarly, in John 2:4, Jesus addresses the timing of his actions, indicating a deeper understanding of his mission, which contrasts with Mary''s immediate grief.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 13, 21, 3, 4, 4, 'why weepest thou?', 'Weeping and Mourning Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of weeping and mourning present in both passages. In John 20:13, the woman weeps for her lost Lord, while Ecclesiastes 3:4 acknowledges a time to weep and mourn.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 13, 42, 24, 17, 17, 'I know not where they have laid him', 'Expressions of Grief and Sadness', 'This connection highlights the emotional state of the characters in both passages. In John, Mary expresses her sorrow over the absence of Jesus, while in Luke, the disciples are described as sad, indicating a shared theme of mourning and loss.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 13, 44, 21, 13, 13, 'why weepest thou', 'Emotional Responses to Loss', 'This connection highlights the theme of deep emotional responses to loss and sacrifice. Both passages emphasize the sorrow of weeping and the readiness to endure suffering for the Lord.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 14, 42, 24, 16, 16, 'knew not that it was Jesus', 'Recognition of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of unrecognized identity. In both passages, the individuals do not initially recognize Jesus, indicating a divine concealment of his identity.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 14, 40, 28, 9, 9, 'knew not that it was Jesus', 'Recognition of the Risen Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of recognizing Jesus after his resurrection. In both passages, individuals encounter Jesus and respond with recognition and worship, emphasizing the transformative experience of seeing the risen Christ.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 14, 41, 16, 9, 9, 'knew not that it was Jesus', 'Mary Magdalene''s Encounter with Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Mary Magdalene''s encounter with Jesus after his resurrection. In John 20:14, she does not recognize him initially, while Mark 16:9 highlights her as the first to see him after he rose.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 14, 43, 21, 4, 4, 'knew not that it was Jesus', 'Recognition of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of not recognizing Jesus. In John 20:14, Mary does not know it is Jesus, and in John 21:4, the disciples also do not recognize Him.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 14, 22, 3, 3, 4, NULL, 'Seeking the Beloved', 'This connection highlights the theme of seeking and recognizing the beloved. In both passages, the characters experience a moment of searching and eventual recognition of Jesus as the one they love.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 14, 42, 24, 31, 31, 'knew not that it was Jesus', 'Recognition of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of recognition in both passages. In John 20:14, Mary does not recognize Jesus, while in Luke 24:31, the disciples'' eyes are opened to know him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 14, 43, 8, 59, 59, 'knew not that it was Jesus', 'Recognition and Concealment of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of recognition and concealment in both passages. In John 20:14, Mary does not recognize Jesus, while in John 8:59, Jesus hides himself from those who seek to harm him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 15, 43, 18, 7, 7, 'whom seekest thou', 'Seeking Jesus Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of seeking Jesus. In John 20:15, Mary seeks the body of Jesus, while in John 18:7, the soldiers inquire about whom they are seeking, identifying Jesus of Nazareth.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 15, 43, 20, 13, 13, 'why weepest thou?', 'Connection of Weeping and Seeking', 'Both passages emphasize the question, ''Why weepest thou?'' highlighting Mary''s sorrow and her search for Jesus. This connection illustrates her emotional state and the urgency of her quest.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 15, 9, 1, 16, 16, 'why weepest thou', 'Connection of Grief and Seeking', 'Both passages emphasize deep grief and seeking. In John, Mary seeks Jesus in her sorrow, while in 1 Samuel, the handmaid expresses her grief and complaint. This connection highlights the emotional state of individuals in distress.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 15, 22, 3, 2, 2, 'whom seekest thou', 'Seeking the Beloved', 'Both passages emphasize the act of seeking someone beloved. In John, Mary seeks Jesus after his resurrection, while in Song of Solomon, the speaker expresses a desire to find the one she loves.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 15, 40, 28, 5, 5, 'whom seekest thou?', 'Seeking Jesus After Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of seeking Jesus after his crucifixion. In John, Mary seeks Jesus, while in Matthew, the angel acknowledges that the women seek him as well.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 15, 41, 16, 6, 6, 'whom seekest thou', 'Resurrection Recognition', 'Both passages emphasize the search for Jesus after his resurrection. In John, Mary seeks Jesus, while in Mark, the angels inform the women that he is not there, highlighting the theme of seeking the risen Christ.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 15, 42, 24, 5, 5, 'whom seekest thou?', 'Seeking the Living', 'This connection highlights the theme of seeking Jesus after his resurrection. Both passages emphasize the misunderstanding of his presence, with Mary seeking the dead in John and the angels questioning why he is sought among the dead in Luke.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 16, 43, 10, 3, 3, 'Rabboni; which is to say, Master', 'Recognition of the Shepherd''s Voice', 'This connection highlights the theme of recognition in both passages. In John 20:16, Mary recognizes Jesus by name, while in John 10:3, the sheep hear the voice of their shepherd and recognize him. Both emphasize the intimate relationship between the shepherd and his sheep.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 16, 43, 1, 38, 38, 'Rabboni; which is to say, Master', 'Connection of Titles for Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the title ''Rabboni'' and ''Rabbi,'' which translate to ''Master.'' This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus'' authority and role as a teacher. The use of these titles in both contexts underscores the significance of Jesus'' identity.', 'keyword', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 16, 1, 22, 1, 1, NULL, 'Divine Call and Response', 'Both passages emphasize a personal call from God, with Jesus calling Mary by name and God calling Abraham. This connection highlights the intimate relationship between the divine and the individual.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 16, 1, 22, 11, 11, NULL, 'Calling by Name', 'This connection highlights the intimate calling of individuals by name. In both passages, a significant figure, Jesus and the angel of the Lord, calls out to a key person, Mary and Abraham, respectively, emphasizing their personal relationship.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 16, 2, 3, 4, 4, NULL, 'Calling by Name', 'This connection highlights the personal calling of individuals by God. In both passages, Jesus and God call out the names of Mary and Moses, respectively, indicating a significant moment of recognition and response.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 16, 2, 33, 17, 17, NULL, 'Recognition of Divine Relationship', 'This connection highlights the personal recognition of Jesus and God. In both passages, individuals are called by name, emphasizing a close relationship with the divine.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 16, 9, 3, 6, 6, NULL, 'Calling and Recognition', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine calling and recognition. In both passages, individuals respond to a call, with Mary recognizing Jesus as ''Master'' and Samuel responding to the Lord''s call.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 17, 43, 16, 28, 28, 'I ascend unto my Father', 'Connection of Ascension to the Father', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' relationship with the Father. In John 20:17, Jesus speaks of ascending to the Father, while John 16:28 mentions His coming forth from the Father and returning to Him.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 20, 17, 49, 4, 8, 10, 'I ascend unto my Father', 'Ascension of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' ascension. Both passages emphasize the significance of ascending to the Father, linking the act of ascension with the giving of gifts to humanity.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
